.TH AWK 1
.SH NAME
awk \- pattern-directed scanning and processing language
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B awk
[
.BI -F " fs"
] [
.BI -v " var=value"
] [
.B -safe
] [
.BI -f " progfile"
] [
.I 'prog'
] [
.IR file ...
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Awk
scans each input
.I file
for lines that match any of a set of patterns.
With each pattern there can be an associated action that will be
performed when a line of a
.I file
matches the pattern.
Each line is matched against the pattern portion
of every pattern-action statement;
the associated action is performed for each matched pattern.
The file name
.B -
means the standard input.
.PP
An input line is made up of fields separated by
white space, or by the field separator
.I fs
specified by the
.B -F
option.
Fields are denoted
.BR $1 ,
.BR $2 ,
\&... ;
.B $0
refers to the entire line.
.PP
A pattern-action statement has the form
.IP
.IB pattern " { " action " }"
.PP
A missing action means print the line;
a missing pattern always matches.
Pattern-action statements are separated by newlines or semicolons.
.PP
An action is a sequence of statements.
Statements include:
.IP
.B "if ("
.I expr
.B )
.I stmt
[
.B else
.IR stmt ]
.br
.B "while ("
.I expr
.B )
.I stmt
.br
.B "for ("
.I expr
.B ;
.I expr
.B ;
.I expr
.B )
.I stmt
.br
.B "for ("
.I var
.B in
.I array
.B )
.I stmt
.br
.B "do"
.I stmt
.B "while ("
.I expr
.B )
.br
.B break
.br
.B continue
.br
.BI { " stmt ..."  }
.br
.I expr
.br
.B print
[
.IR expr-list ]
[
.BI > file
]
.br
.B printf
.I fmt
[
.BI , " expr-list"
]
[
.BI > file
]
.br
.B return
[
.I expr
]
.br
.BI next
.br
.BI exit " [expr]"
.br
.BI delete " array[expr]"
.PP
Statements are terminated by semicolons, newlines, or right braces.
.PP
Patterns are arbitrary Boolean combinations
(with
.BR "! || &&" )
of regular expressions and relational expressions.
Regular expressions are delimited by slashes
and are as defined in
.IR regex (2).
The special patterns
.B BEGIN
and
.B END
may be used to capture control before the first input
line is read and after the last.
.B BEGIN
and
.B END
do not combine with other patterns.
A pattern may consist of two patterns
separated by a comma; in this case, the action is
performed for all lines from an occurrence of the
first pattern to an occurrence of the second.
.PP
Regular expressions may contain the character classes
.BR [...] ,
complemented by
.BR [^...] .
.PP
A relational expression is one of the following:
.IP
.I "expr matchop regexp"
.br
.I "expr relop expr"
.PP
where a
.I relop
is any of the six relational operators in C, and a
.I matchop
is either
.B ~
(matches) or
.B !~
(does not match).
.PP
The mathematical functions
.BR exp ,
.BR log ,
.BR sqrt ,
.BR sin ,
.BR cos ,
and
.BR atan2
are built in.
Other built-in functions:
.TP
.BI length( s )
the length of its argument taken as a string,
or of
.B $0
if no argument.
.TP
.BI rand()
random number on [0,1)
.TP
.BI srand( expr )
sets seed for
.B rand
and returns the previous seed.
.TP
.BI int( x )
truncates to an integer value
.TP
.BI substr( s ", " m  [ ", " n ] )
the at most
.IR n -character
substring of
.I s
starting at position
.IR m ,
counted from 1. If
.I n
is omitted, the rest of the string is used.
.TP
.BI index( s ", " t )
the position in
.I s
where the string
.I t
occurs, 0 if it does not.
.TP
.BI match( s ", " r )
the position in
.I s
where the regular expression
.I r
occurs, or 0 if it does not.
The variables
.B RSTART
and
.B RLENGTH
are set to the position and length of the matched string.
.TP
.BI split( s ", " a  [ ", " fs ] )
splits the string
.I s
into array elements
.IB a [1] ,
.IB a [2] ,
\&...,
.IB a [ n ] ,
and returns
.IR n .
The separation is done with the field separator
.I fs
or with the regular expression
.I fs
if it is given,
otherwise with the one in effect at the time of execution of
.BR split .
.TP
.BI sub( r ", " t  [ ", " s ] )
substitutes
.I t
for the first occurrence of the regular expression
.I r
in the string
.IR s .
If
.I s
is not given,
.B $0
is used.
An ampersand
.RB ( & )
in
.I t
is replaced by the matched substring of
.IR s .
Returns the number of substitutions.
.TP
.BI gsub( r ", " t  [ ", " s ] )
same as
.B sub
except that all occurrences of the regular expression
are replaced.
Returns the number of substitutions.
.TP
.BI sprintf( fmt ", " expr ", " ... )
the string resulting from formatting the expressions
according to the
.IR sys-print (2)
format string
.IR fmt .
.TP
.BI system( cmd )
executes
.I cmd
and returns its exit status.
Not available in
.B -safe
mode.
.TP
.BI tolower( str )
returns a copy of
.I str
with all upper-case characters converted to lower-case.
.TP
.BI toupper( str )
returns a copy of
.I str
with all lower-case characters converted to upper-case.
.PP
The input/output function
.B getline
sets
.B $0
to the next input record from the current input file;
.B "getline x"
sets variable
.I x
instead.
.B "getline < file"
reads from
.IR file .
.PP
The
.B print
statement writes on the standard output (or on a
file if
.BI > file
or
.BI >> file
is present, or on a pipe if
.BI | cmd
is present).
.PP
The
.B printf
statement formats its expression list according to the format (see
.IR sys-print (2)).
.PP
User-defined functions may be declared with the syntax:
.IP
.B "function"
.IB name ( args ") {" " stmts" " }"
.PP
Function arguments are passed by value if scalar and by
reference if array name.
.PP
The options are:
.TP
.BI -F " fs"
Set the input field separator to the string or regular expression
.IR fs .
.TP
.BI -v " var=value"
Assign
.I value
to variable
.I var
before the program is executed.
May be specified multiple times.
.TP
.BI -f " progfile"
Read the awk program from
.I progfile
instead of the command line.
.TP
.B -safe
Disable
.B system
and I/O redirection to prevent access to the
underlying operating system.
.PP
The special variable
.B ENVIRON
is an array of environment variables; the subscripts are names.
It is not available in
.B -safe
mode.
.SH EXAMPLES
.LP
Print second field of each line:
.IP
.B "awk '{ print $2 }'"
.LP
Add up first column, print sum and average:
.IP
.B "awk '{ s += $1 } END { print ""sum"", s, ""average"", s/NR }'"
.LP
Print fields in reverse order:
.IP
.B "awk '{ for (i = NF; i > 0; i--) printf ""%s "", $i; printf ""\\n"" }'"
.LP
Print lines longer than 72 characters:
.IP
.B "awk 'length > 72'"
.SH SOURCE
.B /appl/cmd/awk.b
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR cut (1),
.IR sed (1),
.IR grep (1),
.IR regex (2)
.SH BUGS
Input is limited to the available memory.
There are no explicit conversions between numbers and strings.
To force an expression to be treated as a number add 0 to it;
to force it to be treated as a string concatenate
.B ""
to it.
